1. Azure Key Vault (Secrets & Keys):
      Instead of putting passwords in your Ansible YAML or Git, you store them in Key Vault.
      What it is: A secure "safe" for secrets (passwords), keys (encryption), and certificates.
      How to Verify in Portal: * Go to Key Vaults > Select your Vault > Secrets.
      Tip: If the value looks cut off (common with long Mongo connection strings), use the Azure CLI to see the full value:
          az keyvault secret show --name <secret-name> --vault-name <vault-name> --query value -o tsv
      Check Permissions: Under Access configuration, ensure your app's Managed Identity has "Key Vault Secrets User" (RBAC) or "Get/List" (Access Policy).

2. Azure App Configuration
      While Key Vault stores secrets, App Configuration stores settings (like feature flags or API URLs).
      What it is: A central place to manage non-sensitive settings across all microservices.
      How it connects: Often, a value in App Configuration is just a "Reference" to a secret in Key Vault.   
      How to Verify: Go to App Configuration > Configuration Explorer. Look for the "Key Vault Reference" icon.

3. Database Connections (SQL & Mongo)
    Your Java app needs to talk to a data store. In Azure, these are typically:
    Azure SQL (Relational)
        How to Verify:
